"
    localparam COUNTER_WIDTH = fsm_timeout_COUNTER_WIDTH(TIMEOUT)
"
- defined as
"
    function automatic int fsm_timeout_COUNTER_WIDTH(int TIMEOUT);
        if (TIMEOUT == 0) return 2;
        return $clog2(TIMEOUT) + 2;
    endfunction
"
- correct arguments passed in 
- if guard aswell if timeout is 0
- we calculate the desired width, then add +2 more bits to account for 
    - inclusive end value, TIMEOUT=4, 0,1,2,3,4 not just 0,1,2,3
    - deal with latent increment (explained further down)
[Marc103 + Codex 5.6 - 07/22/26]

"
    input  clk_i,
    input  reset_timer_i,
    output timeout_o
"
- no missing signals
- corret types
[Marc103 + Codex 5.6 - 07/22/26]


"
    always@(posedge clk_i) begin
        // see manual verify about the correctness of this latent timer_increment
        if(reset_timer_i) begin
            timer_increment <= 1;
        end else begin
            timer_increment <= timer > (TIMEOUT - 1);
        end
        
        if(reset_timer_i) begin
            timer <= 1; // timer resets to 1 (not 0)
        end else begin
            if(timer_increment) begin 
                timer <= timer;     // sits on timeout condition
            end else begin
                timer <= timer + 1; // timer increments
            end
        end
    end

    assign timeout_o = (TIMEOUT == 0) || (TIMEOUT == 1) ? 1 : timer > (TIMEOUT - 1);
"
- the basic logic is timer should increment until its timeout value and reset
  (interruptable) when reset_timer_i is asserted
  - the reset state to 1 instead of 0 is intentional, timeout is wrt to the cycle
    in which reset_timer_i is asserted 
- here is the explanation for the timer_increment (why it's delayed behavior is fine)
    Delayed timer increment to stop +1 is intentional and does not affect functionality
    because:
    1. COUNTER_WIDTH is sufficiently large enough to absorb an additional(s) +1 cycles.

    2. timeout_o is dependent on 'timer > (TIMEOUT - 1)'

    3. Upon reset_timer_i, the timer_increment is <= 1 without delay.

    This relieves pressure on the select line so we don't have to do something like
    if(timer > (TIMEOUT - 1)) begin
        timer <= timer;
    else begin
        timer <= timer + 1;
    end
    Where the select is 'timer > (TIMEOUT - 1)' is essentially an adder in series with mux.
- finally we assign timeout_o with the guard check for TIMEOUT == 0 and TIMEOUT == 1
[Marc103 + Codex 5.6 - 07/22/26]

